**Minutes 0–4: scan both problems.** Read both fully and rank them before touching the keyboard. Suppose problem 1 is the pair-counting task — a module-01 pattern, so it goes first.

**Minutes 4–15: brute force, then SUBMIT.** The naive double loop is obviously correct, and on Codility that correctness is worth real points *right now*:

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n; long long k;
    cin >> n >> k;
    vector<long long> a(n);
    for (auto &x : a) cin >> x;

    long long cnt = 0;                  // counts can exceed int
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++)
            if (a[i] + a[j] == k) cnt++;

    cout << cnt << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

This is $O(n^2)$ — at $n = 10^5$ that is $10^{10}$ operations, so the performance groups will TLE. But the correctness groups pass, and roughly half the problem's points are banked before minute 15.

[[fig:m15-partial-credit]]

> [!INTUITION]
> The brute-force submission is your **floor**; the optimized one is your **ceiling**. Locking the floor first means the clock can no longer zero you out on this problem.

**Minutes 15–30: optimize and resubmit.** The hash-map complement count replaces the inner loop:

```cpp
unordered_map<long long, long long> seen;
long long cnt = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    auto it = seen.find(k - a[i]);
    if (it != seen.end()) cnt += it->second;
    seen[a[i]]++;
}
cout << cnt << '\n';
```

$O(n)$ time, $O(n)$ space. Before resubmitting, run the edge checklist: `n == 1` (answer 0), all-equal array with `k` equal to twice the value (counts pairs, not indices twice), negatives, and overflow — two values near $10^9$ sum past `int`, which is why *everything* is `long long`.

**What generalizes:** on any partial-credit platform, the sequence is always *scan → brute force → submit → optimize → resubmit*, with the edge-case checklist run before each submit.

**Why the Codility play fails here.** With all-or-nothing scoring, three half-finished solutions score close to zero. The winning strategy inverts: **fully correct on 1–2 problems beats partials on all 3**.

**Minutes 0–5: read all three, no code.** For each problem, name the pattern (DP? greedy? graph? simulation?) and ask one question: *can I see the full solution path end to end?* Rank by that, not by which is listed first. Given your strengths, the greedy / implementation / DP problem is the likely pick.

[[fig:m15-mock-timeline]]

**Minutes 5–50: lock down problem A to 100%.** Start from the standard skeleton:

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    // ... solve
    return 0;
}
```

Then: state the algorithm and its complexity to yourself *before* coding (hard problems here typically need $O(n \log n)$ or a polynomial DP — check the constraints against the complexity map). Code it, run the samples, then your own tiny cases: `n == 1`, all-equal, boundary values, and a hand-computed known answer. Only submit when you would bet the round on it.

**Minutes 50–85: attack problem B** with the same discipline. **Final 5 minutes:** re-check A and B rather than opening C — a last-minute half-attempt at C is worth nothing under this scoring.

> [!EXAM]
> Skip-and-return still applies *inside* the chosen problems: 10+ minutes with no path forward on B means re-verifying A and salvaging whatever B progress is real, not heroically staring.

> [!KEY]
> Depth beats breadth whenever scoring is binary. Decide your 1–2 targets in the first 5 minutes and spend the other 85 making them bulletproof.
